annotations: Horses
neeigh

Even when the sun comes up, I’m in trouble
 Even when the sun comes up, I’m in trouble

The lines are likely a take on line from Delta bluesman Son House’s “Death Letter Blues”:

You know I didn’t feel so bad
Till the good Lord’s sun went down
I didn’t have a soul to throw my arms around
I didn’t feel so bad until the good Lord’s sun went down
I say I didn’t have a soul to throw my arms around.

Jack White, a man who knows his blues music, riffs on this line in “Dead Leaves and the Dirty Ground.”

That fact that this speaker is stlil in trouble and feels bad even when the sun comes up suggest she has some very hard blues.

People say I’m a one hit wonder
 But what happens when I have two

The lines have a double meaning.

Sharon said in an interview that she’s very lightweight when it comes to Marijuana. She usually takes one hit because because if she takes two she gets really weird.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ylz1mY_Six8

Additionally,  a “one hit wonder” is a musical artist/group that has one, and only one, song that becomes a hit, and they otherwise fade into obscurity as far as the mainstream is concerned. Here Sharon could be facetiously questioning critics saying she only has one notable song by asking the question, “what happens when I have two?”

(Maybe something will change haha
 Sorry, my headphones fell off)

Apparently an outtake from the recording of another song from Are We There, “Nothing Will Change.”

The two vocal tracks are off-key with each other, and Sharon cannot complete the phrase without laughing, then attributing the pitch issues to her headphones falling off.

I washed your dishes
 But I shit in your bathroom

These lines are discussed in an interview with Pitchfork:

There is a line, toward the end, about washing someone’s dishes before taking a shit in their bathroom. She says this is a joke that merely stayed in place—the product of a very late and giggly night in the studio with her band—but her willingness to allow it to become permanent is telling.

description.plain:
According to Sharon Van Etten, the lyrics for “Seventeen” were inspired by New York City, and the changes she saw in the city in all the time she lived there:



“Seventeen” just feels like my New York song. This is talking about living somewhere long enough to see the changes that I have. I’ve been here fifteen years. To be like, chasing neighborhoods constantly, walking down the street and seeing a place that’s closed that I used to hang out in, in a neighborhood you can no longer afford, but then you see kids younger than you moving in, things like that, constantly – it’s just the New York Story.

The lyrics see Van Etten musing about her past seventeen-year-old self, offering a perspective on the tribulations of life, and how people can grow, change, and ultimately find their place in the world.

annotations:
Someone throws the ladder down
 Still don’t know what I have found

When she was at her lowest, she finally decided to leave that abusive relationship behind her. However, a part of her is still trying to find what all the pain she’s been through meant.

Why does this love hurt so much? She doesn’t have the answer. She felt as she suffered for nothing.
We’re a half-mast flag in wind

Flags fly at half mast in mourning, as after a tragedy.



A flag at half mast “in wind” suggests further injury, being slapped around while already in pain.

You say I am genuine
 I see your backhand again

Her lover tells her she is “genuine,” that she is real, authentic, which is a compliment. However, the second line suggests that this is possibly a “backhanded” compliment, something that seems a compliment but is actually an insult. “Backhand” also has slightly violent connotations, as in a slap with the back of the hand.

description.plain:
Van Etten has said that her second album Epic was inspired by her recovery from a bad relationship:

This guy didn’t even let me have a guitar. I don’t have any bitterness toward him because he kicked my ass into leaving Tennessee. But the record isn’t about him; it’s about me getting over that situation.”

An album later, Sharon returns to these memories that remain with her- like serpents whose bitterness she still remembers.

body.plain:
Van Etten has said that her second album Epic was inspired by her recovery from a bad relationship:

This guy didn’t even let me have a guitar. I don’t have any bitterness toward him because he kicked my ass into leaving Tennessee. But the record isn’t about him; it’s about me getting over that situation.”

An album later, Sharon returns to these memories that remain with her- like serpents whose bitterness she still remembers.

annotations: I don’t want mine to this time

Acknowledging the mutability and capriciousness of life she proposes the question: If everything changes then why is only one person in the relationship subject to these changes while the other remains the same?

She also seems to reference the fact that she is accustomed to changing for another person and perhaps maybe this time she’s satisfied with who she is and feels that she shouldn’t be subjected to changing for the other person yet again.

Sitting in the back of the room
 With a boy you could own

She likens her role in the relationship as stifled despite her own perceived self-worth/self value. Hence in contrast with her own talents or gifts she “sits in the back of the room” restrained, diminished and stagnating with someone who frankly isn’t on her level or someone “you could own”
Close in on my black eye

The words ‘close in’ shows that the abuse she is suffering may not be obvious at first, you have to really look at her to know whats happening in her life. People often can’t detect if someone’s being abused unless you look for it.
Collaging girls
Sharon suspects her partner has been sleeping with other girls who have had plastic surgery. She is insulting the girls by saying they are naturally ugly and needed surgery to look good.
Looking for your crimes

Sharon is trying to find a fault with her lover, or something she can tell him off about (maybe she suspects adultery). At the same time, she feels guilty. Serpents have been used in the Adam and Eve story as a symbolism of giving in to guilt, and Sharon could be hinting at this same guilty feeling.

You hold the mirror well
 To everybody else
Her ex is great at holding up the mirror and pointing out other people’s problems, but won’t look inward towards his own.

You enjoy sucking on dreams
 So I will fall asleep with someone other than you

Sharon used to be in a relationship with a very controlling partner.


When he would go on tour I’d play guitar and he would hear about it and he’d get upset. He got really mad at me one time.

He broke my guitar. He later apologized about it. I don’t think he meant for it to scare me, but it did


His emotional abuse is what caused her to eventually leave the relationship.
Serpents in my mind
A metaphor for how painful it is to think about their relationship. It’s like snakes crawling through her mind.

description.plain:
The first single off Sharon Van Etten’s fifth studio album, Remind Me Tomorrow.

Described as “faster, firmer and more boisterous” than her previous work, “Comeback Kid” foretold the album’s sonic direction and the shift in Van Etten’s sound from guitar-based to relying more on synths.

According to Van Etten, she wrote the track on the piano, even before beginning her experimentations with synthesizers.
